{"/service/ndnp/wa/batch_wa_columbia_ver01/data/sn88085947/00211108587/1908011401/0115.xml":{"full_text":"4\nCONVICT HAS NO REDRESS\nNO MA TTER WHA T HAPPENS\nFROM THE VIEWPOINT OF THE\nCELL\nBy Jessie M. Partlon\nWho in a prison is to be be\nlieved?\nThat's the great question which\nconfronts the investigator. It Is\nalso the reason why reforms are\nbo often delayed.\nOut of prison the man who has\n\"done time\" is deeply distrustful of\nyour good intentions, suspicious of\nevery one, reticent to the point of\ndumbness, until someone will\nvouch for the stranger's honesty.\nWhen that is done, as it has hap\npened to me in several cases, the\nfloodgates of speech are loosened\nand the wrongs of years are laid\n\"FOR SIX YEARS A MAN WAS KEPT IN ASTEEL CAGE AND\nPOINTED OUT AS THE PRISON DEMON.\"\nbare. What dark secrets, what in\nstances of petty graft, what glaring\ninjustice, the convict broods on.\nNo instance of prison mismanage\nment is hidden from the men in\nside. By a system of wireless\ntelegraphy they learn all that tran\nspires and can tell the pet sin of\nevery member of the board of man\nagers.\nIt is the \"old timer\" who tells\nJthe green boy the best means of\ndealing with the guards; shows him\nhow he can go through his term\nwith the least labor\u2014perhaps not\nthat he hates work, but merely as a\nmeans of \"hitting back\" at the sys\ntem.\nThe newcomer is made to under\nstand that the yord of a convict\ncarries no weight; and learns from\nthe experience of others that no\nmatter what happens in prison\nthere is no redress for him.\nWe on the outside never hear of\nthe cruel taunts, the man baiting,\nthe jibes and insults and vile\nthreats that the convict suffers. But\nwe always hear of the \"dangerous\ncriminal who suddenly and with\nout warning knifes a keeper or\nspreads panic In a gang of fellow\nprisoners until he is caught, beaten\nand subdued.\nTaking a list of such happenings\nat random from the daily papers I\nhunted up men who had been in\nprison at the time these desperate\n\"assaults\" were committed. The\nstories told were wonderfully dif\nferent from those given out by the\nprison management for publication.\nWe must admit there are desper\nate and hardened men in prison.\nBut it is self-evident that the more\na man is punished the more hard\nened and debased he becomes.\nFor six years a man was kept In\na steel cage in the Ohio peniten\ntiary and pointed out to spectators\nas the \"prison demon.\"\nHEAT\nIn the Right Place\nAt the Right Time\nThat s it\u2014where you want it\u2014when\nyou want it \u2014and ii you only\nknew how easy it is lo carry Irom\nroom to room \u2014and how much\ncheery comlorl you can have wilh a\nPERFECTION\nOil Heater\nwith SmokelctM D\u00abvle\u00ab)\nYou would no longer be wilhoul one.\n\"No smoke \u2014no smell \u2014(his is the\nPtrftttitn maxim. Because the smokeless\ndevice is smokeless you can have\nJirecl. plowing heat from every ounce\nol oil. Brass (on* holds 4 quarts\nburns 9 hours. An ornament any\nwhere\u2014linished in japan and nickeL\nEvery heater warranted.\nHe heard his own visciousness\ntaunted daily. One day he took a\npiece of wire, sharpened one end by\nrubbing it against the bars, and\ntried to stab the next man that ap\nproached his cage.\nFinally, the ebb and flow of poli\ntics landed a man in the warden's\nchair who believed in other men.\nHe took Ira Marlatt out of his cage\nand today he is running errands\nand behaving like a human crea\nture instead of a beast. I believe\nit is not the \"bad man\" who gets\nthe blows and vicious treatment\ninside the prison, but the weak and\nhelpless and stupid.\nThe man who by a long life of\ncrime and wide experience in pris-\nons might be capable of killing a\nkeeper is usually let severely alone.\nOne of the first things such a man\ndoes on being committed is to\nserve notice on the guards that he\nwill not stand for any \"monkey\nbusiness.'' They know he means\nwhat he says. These are the\n\"hoores\" of the prison world.\nThey walk apart, protected even\nhere by their daring and contempt\nfor life.\nForty per cent of all Inmates of\nreformatories served time in other\ninstitutions, 20 per cent are very\nunsatisfactory under parole, and 10\nper cent of all committed return\nto a life of crime within a year\nafter being released.\nPunishment does not reform.\nThe atmosphere which convicts\nbreathe in prison contributes to\ntheir further downfall. Instead of\nbuilding up will power and prepar\ning the wrecks and failures of so\nciety for liberty, the prison usually\nfilches what little manhood the con\nvict has left and sends him forth\nworse instead of better.\nIn the next article Miss Partlon\nwill discuss \"The Value of a Man.\"\nVISSCHER SHOOTS OFFICER.\nOMAHA. Jan. 14.\u2014Will Visscher,\njournalist and humorist, shot and\nseriously injured Patrol Conductor\nPeter Dillon while he was being\ntaken to the police station In a pa\ntrol wagon, charged with drunken\nness. According to the statements\nof the conductor and Driver Van\nDeroord, the shooting was entirely\nunprovoked.\nVisscher is well known on the\nPacific coast through his connec\ntion with Portland and Tacoma\nnewspapers. He served for one\nterm as grand commander of the\nstate G. A. R.\nto your n g ine\n_ paper\u2014lt gives a bril\nlull). study light. Equipped with the latest improved centnl drill\nburner. Made \u00abt braas. nickel plated. Every lamp warranted.\nWrite our nearest agenry lor descriptive circular il you don I Ud\nlbs 1 uicclion Oil Healer or Rayo Lamp at your dealer's.\nSTANDARD OIL COMPANY\n(Incorporated)\nCITIZENS KNOW\nWHAT THEY\nWANT\nREJECT EXPENSIVE ENGINEER\nPLAN TO SETTLE GRADE\nSEPARATION AND DEMAND\nTHAT STREETS BE LEFT\nOPEN.\nThe N, P. grade separation mass\nmeeting at the City hall last night\nrefused to consider a proposition\nof the 150,000 club that the city\nhire an engineer of international\nreputation to devise a plan of ad\njusting the company's tracks\nthrough the city.\nProperty holders were unable to\ndiscern where the expense of such\nservice would be justified, espe\ncially since there were no means\nof binding the company to accept\nsuch plans even were they perfect\nly satisfactory to property owners\ninterested. The cost of such an en\ngineer would be enormous and it is\ndifficult to see by what process the\nclub justified such action. In addi\ntion to these objections the proper\nty owners feel certain that they\ncould decide how they wanted the\ncompany to establish its trackage\nwithout expert and experienced ad\nvice.\nAside from this no definite re\nsult was accomplished last night,\naside from the opportunity afforded\nfor an expression of sentiment.\nThis sentiment was unanimous for\nopen streets where the company\nproposes to close them in elevating\nits tracks,\nOn behalf of the company, E. J.\nCannon substituted an attitude of\ntechnical explanation and objec\ntion for his previous one of de\nfiance.\nFor a short space of time his at\ntitude was belligerent because of\ndislike to W. B. Roberts, at whose\nbehest the gathering was there. On\naccount of this attitude he started\nto prolong the session so that lit\ntle time could he given to the main\nquestion\u2014the leaving open of\nBrowne st. \u2014by interrogating each\none of the citizens as to his name\nand what property interest he held.\nJudge Poindexter forestalled the\nrailroad attorney by objecting to\nthe procedure. Mr. Cannon then\nasked all those whose interests\nwould be effected to rise, and only\nfour people remained seated. But\nthe Browne st. topic was again\nsidestepped. Instead of tackling it\nat once, it was 9 o'clock before the\nattorney finally reached it. He be\ngan, with the assistance of the\nmaps, to outline the grade separa\ntion plans fro mthe west, working\neast until Washington st. was\nreached. He then adopted another\ncourse and drew attention to the\nfact that during his three years'\nresidence here he has witnessed\nthe funerals of five small children\nwho were ground under the wheals\nof the trains on account of the dan\ngers caused by the tracks being on\nthe present grade.\n\"At the rate I am asked to make\nconcessions to the city,\" Cannon\nsaid, \"it will cost $10,000 a day.\nThe very most I have been able to\nget out of the company for changes\nis $80,000 and we must keep within\nthis limit. The project will re\nquire an expense of about $3,500,-\n--000. About 1,400 of your people\nare now on our payroll and the\nwork will necessitate still greater\npayrolls.\"\nMr. Cannon reached Browne st.\nby referring to the dangers of the\nkind of girders that would be nec\nessary were Browne st. to be left\nopen. He still held to the theory\nthat it would be impossible to open\nBrowne st. and do away with the\nvery dangers the company intends\ndoing away with by grade separa\ntion. The depot will be moved\nnearer to Division st. and will cost\nabout $300,000. Twelve tracks are\nplanned to pass in front of it. W.\nH. Ludden led the fight for open\nstreets. The road proposes to close\nThird, Oak, Cedar, Ash, Browne\nand Bernard.\nJudge Miles Poindexter grasped\nthe drift of the meeting when he\nsaid that the citizens were not yet\nready to go into the minute de\ntails. Some repartee passed be\ntween Attorney W. L. Ludden, W.\nB. Roberts and the railroad man,\nbut at no time did the discussion\nwax warm. Neither side seemed\nto have gained any points. The\nonly two councilmen present were\nN. S. Pratt and Capt. John Gray.\nNeither one took part in the dis\ncussions.\nW. B. Roberts made the principal\ntalk when he cailed the meeting to\norder. He said that ever since he\nfirst made up his mind, he has been\nopposed to grade separation and\nthat the only ideal way was to sink\nthe tracks. In this way no lives\nwould be lost and tho property\nrights of the people would be pro\ntected. No unsightly wall through\nthe city is desired. There was no\ndiscussion as to wdiether a concrete\nwall and steel trestles would be\nused or a sandbank and steel\ntrestles. The opposition stood for\nthe opening of all streets notwith\nstanding the cost. Mr. Canno made\nno promises ami the speakers did\nnot attempt to exact promises.\nAbout 9:30 o'clock Mayor Moore,\nHarry Gibbon and A. L. White\nreached the council chambers with\na 150,000 club resolution which was\nvoted down decisively.\nREFORMS SLAUGHTER HOUSE\nChris Sorenson's slaughter\nhouse, which was ordered closed\nby the health department on ac\ncount of the unclean state in which\nIt was kept, was allowed to he re\nopened this morning after an in\nspection by Otto Bittrick, who re\nported that it is now in a clean,\nsanitary condition.\nSPOKANE PRESS, TUESDAY, JANUARY 14, 1908.\nThaw's Lawyers Snapped After Court\nSpecial snapshot for this newspaper by Staff Photographer Howard\nDoncourt shows Thaw's leading lawyers, Martin W. Littleton on the\nleft and Daniel O'Reilly on the right, leaving the criminal courts\nbuilding after court session.\nSLAPPED JONES\nAND HUBBARD\nA slam was given Congressman\nJones by the State Federation of\nLabor in the adoption of a resolu\ntion declaring for parcels posts.\nJones recently had gone 00 record\nas opposing this law In the inter\nests, it was believed, of the express\ncompanies and the mercantile as\nsociations.\nMany resolutions were adopted\nand as a result there will be a num\nber of laws introduced into the\nnext meeting of the state legisla\nture to remedy existing evils and\nabuses perpetrated by corpora\ntions.\nIt is proposed to take the ap\npointment of state labor commis\nsioner out of the hands of the gov\nernor and make it an elective of\nfice. Commissioner Hubabrd, the\npresent incumbent of the office,\nwas roasted by the convention as a\ntool of the corporations and al\nthough a member of the Locomo\ntive Engineers' brotherhood he was\npictured as being blind to the most\nsimple duties devolving on him.\nThe resolution which brought on\nthe greatest debate in the meeting\nwas introduced by the Seattle cen\ntral body and was in opposition to\nclosing theaters on Sunoday. It was\nmade plain that many of the dele\ngates present did not oppose the\nkeeping open of theaters from a\nmoral standpoint as much as from\nthe fact that labor is demanding\na shorter workday and Is opposed\nto a seven day week. To have\nadopted the resolution would place\nthe labor men of the state in the\nposition of favoring working every\nday in the week. There was also a\nvery large number of delegates\nwho were opposed to the resolu\ntion from a purely moral stand\npoint and the resolution was voted\ndown by a vote of 3 to 1.\nIt leaked out after action had\nbeen taken on the resolution that\nwhen it came up in the committee\nit was laid on the table, but the\nSeattle delegates insisted that they\nwould bring a minority report intp\nthe convention with the result that\nlabor throughout the state is on\nrecord for Sunday closing.\nGOOD HINT FOR\nSPOKANE\nA band of young Seattle men will\ncall a conference within a few\ndays at which a movement to open\nhouses or stranger's clubs in Seat\ntle will be started. These coffee\nhouses will be operated as to fur\nnish a lounging place for young\nmen, where influences will be for\nthe best. Portland has lately open\ned such coffee houses, and in each\nplace they have been very success\nful in counteracting the influence\nof the saloons among young men.\nThe Young Men's Civic club,\nwhich has been holding meetings\nat the Y. M. C. A., under the direc\ntion of Rev. J. M. Dean, has had\nthis plan under discussion for some\ntime aud after thorough investiga\ntion has decided to call a meeting\nto finance the first coffee house.\nThese coffee houses are so equlp\npe das to furnish a club room to\nyoung men who have no other\nplace to spend their leisure time.\nThey are equipped with reading\nrooms, and it is planned to install\na circulating library in the pro\nposed Seattle coffee house.\nThe engagement of Miss Kate\nM. Beeman, of Maine, to Edward\nW. Berry, of Spokane, is an\nnounced in a Boston dispatch.\nHave a Suit Made Tomorrow for\n$18.00\nAt the Scotch Tailor? where it will he made right here In Spo\nkane in our own shop. This Is the greatest suit offer ever\nmade for it embraces a choice, of our stock of imported and do\nmestic woolens worth up to $80.00.\nA Snappy, Smart Business Suit\nFor Less Than a Ready Made.\nAll we ask is that inspecti our goods and we guarantee a\nperfect fit or you need not take the garment. Only the best of\nlinings and trimmings used.\nTHE SCOTCH TAILORS\n240 Riverside Avenue\nWORKMEN\nWIDE AWAKE\nSpokane delegates who attended\nthe convention of the State Federa\ntion of Labor are well pleased with\nwhat was accomplished. They\nspeak in the highest terms of the\nmen and women who composed the\nconvention. One of the Tacoma pa\npers make the statement that it\nwould be hard to distinguish the\nconvention from a meeting of busi\nness and professional men. The\npurpose of the delegates assembled\nwas also so plain to the outsider\nthat it occasioned general com\nment.\nThe purpose of the convention Is\nfor the exchange of ideas and to\nbring all labor bodies throughout\nthe state into closer harmony and\nto keep in touch with the general\nlabor movement in this section of\nthe country.\nThe representatives made it\nplain through resolutions adopted,\nthat the workingmen of the state\nare fully informed in regard to the\nrepresentatives of the state in con\ngress. In adopting a resolution de\nnouncing Congressman Humphrey's\nship subsidy steal, as it was called\nin the convention, they repudiated\nthe statements made by that gen\ntleman that he was backed up by\nlocal labor in his efforts to reach\ninto the pockets of the people in\nthe interests of the ship building\ntrust.\nSPOKANE IS LABOR'S\nSTRONGHOLD\nReturning delegates to the State\nFederation of Labor state that it is\ngenerally conceeded that this city\nis the best organized from a labor\nstandpoint of any in the state. In\nTacoma the Carpenters' union\nnumbers about 300 men, while the\nSpokane union has about 1,000 at\npresent and when the building sea\nson is active this number is near\n1,100. While the difference be\ntween other unions is not so great,\nyet it is greatly in favor of this\ncity.\nTACOMA JAPS HIRE\nWHITE LAUNDRYMEN\nA peculiar labor feature com\nmented on in Tacoma at the recent\nfederation convention, is the fact\nthat Japanese owners of laundries\nemploy white help. This is true in\na number of instances, only whites\nbeing employed, although the laun\ndries are owned by Japanese.\nHANNA MADE COADJUTOR.\nSAN FRANCISCO. Jan., 14.\u20141t\nhas been learned today that the\nappointment of Rev, Dr. Edward\nJ. Hanna as coadjutor archbishop\nof San Francisco, succeeding late\nArchbishop Montgomery, will be\nproclaimed today at the Vatican.\nRICH GIFT TO UNIVERSITY.\nRENO, New, Jan. If\u2014Clarence\nMackay, the telegraph magnate,\nwill spend $100,000 in beautifying\nthe campus of the University of Ne\nvada surrounding the statute of his\nfather, John W. Mackay. A $75,000\nlibrary is included among proposed\nnew buildings.\nWe Sell Dr. Peter Fahrney's\nKuriko $1.25\nOle-Oid 50c\nWATSON DRUG CO.,\n233 Riverside Aye.\nNO REDUCTION IN\nWAGES CONSIDERED\nPres. Jones of the Tacoma cham\nber of commerce came near raising\na row when, in welcoming the Fed\neration of Labor delegates to Ta\ncoma. he intimated that labor\nshould be patient while wages were\nreduced as a result of unfavorable\nfinancial conditions. Organizer C.\nO. Young, the next speaker, made\nit very plain to Mr. Jones and all\nothers present that labor through\nout the state would not submit to\na reduction in wages without a\nfight. He pointed out to Mr. Jones\nand others assembled at the con\nvention that the very best way to\nbring about a return of prosperity\nwas by maintaining wages.\nSTOLE TAFT'S OVERCOAT.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 14.\u2014Following\nhis speech at Cooper Union, Secre\ntary of War William H. Taft visit\ned several clubs and restaurants or.\nthe East Side, and consequently\nRepublic Has WorK\nable Ores at\nIntervals for\nFive Miles\nWHAT ABOUT DEPTH OX THE FISSURE? What ahout the\nwell-established German theory, brought to mind by Prof. Aughey,\nof continuity with depth\u2014that the depth of a fissure should equal\nits length? Then the Kurekn Assure should be FIVE MILES DEEP!\nWhen Its great length is considered Its present superficial explora\ntion appears like A MERE SCRATCHING AT THE SURFACE.\nAnd It is so. The Eureka zone has had no opportunity as yet to\nprove its extent and richness. Only one other zone\non the NORTH AMERICAN CONTINENT EXCEEDS, OR\nRATHER DID EXCEED THE MAGNITUDE AND POS\nSIBILITIES OF THE EUREKA GOLD ZONE AND\nTHAT IS, OF COURSE, THE INCOMPARABLE COM\nSTOCK. The suspension of work at the six hundred foot level on\nthe Comstock lode would have Faulted In an entirely different story\n\u2014in the loss of millions in the precious metals and its reputation\nas the greatest \"mother lode\" extant.\nThis company plans to sink a three-compartment main working\nshaft from the most logical surface point to a low-level depth. At\nproper entervala drifts will be driven on the ore body. It Is the\nplan to keep the Bhaft in the ore or in close proximity to the ore,\nreachable by sluirt cross cuts, the entire depth. In this way the\nnature and value of the ore will be known dally as the work\nprogresses. Thus when bonzaza shoots are encountered share\nholders may be apprised at once of the facts and the company\ncan take such steps as it may deem proper to exploit and market\nthe ore. Long before the depth of two thousand feet is reached\nthis mine will be one of the GREATEST GOLD MINES IN THE\nWEST \u2014or the judgment of many long experienced mining men Is\nat fault. This is strong, optimistic language, it may be thought,\nbut it is entirely justified by the facts. For the amount of work\ndone no golden-laden fissure in the West bus so many valuable\ncharacteristics or so much promise of EXTRAORDINARY results\nas the fissure on which our ground Is located. Mine development\nhas never been disappointing on this fissure. Mill methods and ex\ntravagant management have been disappointing, perhaps, but the\nmines themselves have never failed and have never been disap\npointing.\nFor further information fill out and mail us the slip below. Price of stock\nadvances on the 20th Lust.\nDon't lose your opportunity to sign up.\nSyndicated Deep Mines,\n522-23 Jamieson Block,\nSpokane, Wash.\nGentlemen: Please send me your\ndescriptive printed matter and price\nof stock.\nName\nAddress\nBat for contentment.\nEat for good nature.\nBoth are the result of physical\nhealth.\nThe most nutritious food made\nfrom flour is\nUneeda Biscuit\nEvery bite a mouthful of energy.\nfa>ff* In dust and\nmoisture proof packages.\n\\J NATIONAL BISCUIT COMPANY\nwas obliged to go homo in the early\nhours of the morning without an\novercoat. When he looked for the\ncoat at the end of the Cooper\nUnion meeting it was not to be\nfound, and a search had been In\nstituted for it when some one dis\ncovered a boy trying to get out of\nthe building with it. The coat was\nrecovered but the boy escaped.\nBicycles Bought\nsold and repaired. Motor cycle\nrepairing a specialty. First\nclass work.\nKNEPPER HOSLER,\n209 Browne Near Front.\nThe Rembrant Studio\nunder new management, are\nmaking fine cabinets from $2.50\nup. First class work guaran\need.\n402 NICHOLS BLOCK.\nOver Berry's.\nTho Spokane Press delivered to\nany part of the city fer 25 cents\nper month.\nSYNDICATED\nDEEP MINES\n522-23 JAMIESON BLOCK.\nJ. E. McFarland, Sec'y-Treaa.\nin charge.\nLIKE AN OASIS\nIn the desert of \"money\nraising sales,\" \"clearing\nsales,\" \"rummage sales,\n\"alteration sales,\" \"mark\ned down sales,\" appears\nthe welcome announce\nment of the\nBLACK ttYVI HIT\nM/V SHOP\nNEW HATS\nreceived tills week \u2014$2.50\nand $3.50.\nS8 HOWARD.\n\"Republic,\nthe\nGreatest\nMining\nCamp of\nWashing\nton\nIs foremost In the\nstale as regards de\nvelopment work, and\nin the extent of the\npayable character of\nits immense ore bodies\nThere is not a reputa\nble engineer In the\ncountry who would not\ndeclare that for uni\nformity of ore bodies\nat tallied, and for tho\ncertainty or high val\nues, not even the rich\nmineral areas of Ross\nland and the Boundary\ncan equal it. Capital\nintelligently expended\nshould reap sunilrous\nly. No greater oppor\ntunity ever existed.\"\u2014\nStaff correspondence,\nThe Mining World.","height":"27400","width":"23384"}}
